IV. How omphacium is made, just before the grape begins to mature, I have already described in my section on unguents ⁶3 I will now notice its medi- cinal properties. It also cures sores in a moist part of the body, such as the mouth, tonsils or genitals. It is very helpful for clearness of visionf and is good for scabrous eyelids, sores in the corners of the eyeS, films on the eyes, running sores in any part of the body, flabby scars, and bones with a slimy pus on them.d Its strength can be modified by adding honey or raisin wine. Omphacium is also good for dysentery, spitting of blood, and quinsy.

Only when bones are exposed because of wounds or dangerous rodent ulcers do we see them “purulent.” The truth seems to be that Pliny misread the Greek that appears in Dioscorides (V. 5) as οὖλα πλαδαρά, ὦτα πυορροοῦνται “flabby gums and pus in the ears.‘’ I .e. οὖλα has been confused with οὐλαὶ and ὦτα with ὀστᾶ. The suggestion of Hardouin, adopted by Sillig, to read auribus for the ossibus of the MSS„ clears away the second difficulty, but leaves the first untouohed.
